1.english: Then Pharisees and scribes came to Jesus from Jerusalem, saying,
1.wedau: maratagogi [pharisees] ma tauviharaharamanahi neꞌi da Yesu au jerusalem riwa ipa

2.english: “Why do your disciples disobey the tradition of the elders? For they don’t wash their hands when they eat bread.”
2.wedau: [“why] rura ami tauvotaghotagho [disobey]  [tradition] ana  [elders?] yamna tauhi [don’t] [wash] ahi nimana maranaina tauhi [eat] [bread”]

3.english: He answered them, “Why do you also disobey the commandment of God because of your tradition?
3.wedau: tauna [answered] hita [“why] rura omi maitehi [disobey]  [commandment] ana God yamna ana ami [tradition?]
3.translation_notes: Primary dimension: Wisdom (0.64); Strong secondary: Love

4.english: For God commanded, ‘Honor your father and your mother,’ and, ‘He who speaks evil of father or mother, let him be put to death.’
4.wedau: yamna God ririweiya [‘honor] ami Tamatei ma ami [mother’] ma [‘he] aiyai pa [evil] ana Tamatei bo hinana ita tauna  terei da [death’]
4.translation_notes: Primary dimension: Wisdom (0.69); Strong secondary: Love

5.english: But you say, ‘Whoever may tell his father or his mother, “Whatever help you might otherwise have gotten from me is a gift devoted to God,”
5.wedau: tuna omi riwa [‘whoever] ita riwehi ana Tamatei bo ana hinana [“whatever] [help] omi ita [otherwise] ana [gotten] au tau   [gift] [devoted] da [god”]
5.translation_notes: Primary dimension: Wisdom (0.81); Strong secondary: Love

6.english: he shall not honor his father or mother.’ You have made the commandment of God void because of your tradition.
6.wedau: tauna ina egha [honor] ana Tamatei bo [mother’] omi ana rura  [commandment] ana God [void] yamna ana ami [tradition]

7.english: You hypocrites! Well did Isaiah prophesy of you, saying,
7.wedau: omi [hypocrites!] ahiahina rura aisaiya [prophesy] ana omi riwa ipa

8.english: ‘These people draw near to me with their mouth, and honor me with their lips; but their heart is far from me.
8.wedau: [‘these] rava [draw] turiyai da tau maitehi ahi [mouth] ma [honor] tau maitehi ahi [lips;] tuna ahi urana  [far] au tau

9.english: And in vain do they worship me, teaching as doctrine rules made by men.’ ”
9.wedau: I ma au [vain] rura tauhi [worship] tau viharaharamana  [doctrine] [rules] rura au [men’] [”]
9.translation_notes: Primary dimension: Power (0.72); Strong secondary: Wisdom

10.english: He summoned the multitude, and said to them, “Hear, and understand.
10.wedau: tauna [summoned]  [multitude] ma riwa da hita [“hear] ma [understand]

11.english: That which enters into the mouth doesn’t defile the man; but that which proceeds out of the mouth, this defiles the man.”
11.wedau: raketana aiyai rui au  [mouth] [doesn’t] [defile]  [man;] tuna raketana aiyai [proceeds] hopu ana  [mouth] ina [defiles]  [man”]

12.english: Then the disciples came, and said to him, “Do you know that the Pharisees were offended when they heard this saying?”
12.wedau: maratagogi  tauvotaghotagho neꞌi ma riwa da tauna [“do] omi haramaneꞌi raketana  [pharisees]  [offended] maranaina tauhi [heard] ina [saying?”]

13.english: But he answered, “Every plant which my heavenly Father didn’t plant will be uprooted.
13.wedau: tuna tauna [answered] [“every] [plant] aiyai au marei Tamatei [didn’t] [plant] ina  [uprooted]

14.english: Leave them alone. They are blind guides of the blind. If the blind guide the blind, both will fall into a pit.”
14.wedau: [leave] hita [alone] tauhi  [blind] [guides] ana  [blind] tora  [blind] [guide]  [blind] ruwagha ina [fall] au  [pit”]

15.english: Peter answered him, “Explain the parable to us.”

16.english: So Jesus said, “Do you also still not understand?
16.wedau: yamna Yesu riwa [“do] omi maitehi [still] egha [understand?]
16.translation_notes: Primary dimension: Wisdom (0.77); Strong secondary: Love

17.english: Don’t you understand that whatever goes into the mouth passes into the belly, and then out of the body?
17.wedau: [don’t] omi [understand] raketana [whatever] nae au  [mouth] [passes] au  [belly] ma maratagogi hopu ana  [body?]

18.english: But the things which proceed out of the mouth come out of the heart, and they defile the man.
18.wedau: tuna  [things] aiyai [proceed] hopu ana  [mouth] neꞌi hopu ana  urana ma tauhi [defile]  oroto

19.english: For out of the heart come evil thoughts, murders, adulteries, sexual sins, thefts, false testimony, and blasphemies.
19.wedau: yamna hopu ana  urana neꞌi [evil] [thoughts] [murders] [adulteries] [sexual] ghohaꞌapoapoe [thefts] [false] inavi heghehi ma [blasphemies]
19.translation_notes: Primary dimension: Power (0.50); Low harmony verse (distinctive emphasis)

20.english: These are the things which defile the man; but to eat with unwashed hands doesn’t defile the man.”
20.wedau: ina   [things] aiyai [defile]  [man;] tuna da [eat] maitehi [unwashed] nimana [doesn’t] [defile]  [man”]

21.english: Jesus went out from there, and withdrew into the region of Tyre and Sidon.
21.wedau: Yesu nae hopu au kampa ma [withdrew] au  [region] ana [tyre] ma [sidon]

22.english: Behold, a Canaanite woman came out from those borders, and cried, saying, “Have mercy on me, Lord, you son of David! My daughter is severely possessed by a demon!”
22.wedau: [behold]  [canaanite] vaivine neꞌi hopu au raketana [borders] ma [cried] riwa ipa [“have] nuwaboyei au tau Guyau omi natuna ana [david!] au natuna  [severely] [possessed] au  [demon!”]
22.translation_notes: Primary dimension: Wisdom (0.82); Strong secondary: Love

23.english: But he answered her not a word. His disciples came and begged him, saying, “Send her away; for she cries after us.”
23.wedau: tuna tauna [answered] ana egha  riwana ana tauvotaghotagho neꞌi ma [begged] tauna riwa ipa [“send] ana [away;] yamna tauna [cries] muriyai [us”]

24.english: But he answered, “I wasn’t sent to anyone but the lost sheep of the house of Israel.”
24.wedau: tuna tauna [answered] [“i] [wasn’t] vivohi da [anyone] tuna  [lost] [sheep] ana  numa ana [israel”]

25.english: But she came and worshiped him, saying, “Lord, help me.”
25.wedau: tuna tauna neꞌi ma [worshiped] tauna riwa ipa [“lord] [help] [me”]

26.english: But he answered, “It is not appropriate to take the children’s bread and throw it to the dogs.”
26.wedau: tuna tauna [answered] [“it]  egha [appropriate] da varahai  [children’s] [bread] ma [throw] tauna da  [dogs”]

27.english: But she said, “Yes, Lord, but even the dogs eat the crumbs which fall from their masters’ table.”
27.wedau: tuna tauna riwa [“yes] Guyau tuna ma  [dogs] [eat]  [crumbs] aiyai [fall] au ahi [masters’] [table”]

28.english: Then Jesus answered her, “Woman, great is your faith! Be it done to you even as you desire.” And her daughter was healed from that hour.
28.wedau: maratagogi Yesu [answered] ana [“woman] ghe vavahagha  ami [faith!]  tauna [done] da omi ma  omi [desire”] ma ana natuna  yawahanihi au raketana [hour]

29.english: Jesus departed from there, and came near to the sea of Galilee; and he went up into the mountain, and sat there.
29.wedau: Yesu [departed] au kampa ma neꞌi turiyai da  topana ana [galilee;] ma tauna nae au au  dobuna ma [sat] kampa

30.english: Great multitudes came to him, having with them the lame, blind, mute, maimed, and many others, and they put them down at his feet. He healed them,
30.wedau: ghe vavahagha [multitudes] neꞌi da tauna [having] maitehi hita  [lame] [blind] [mute] [maimed] ma anatapuhi ghehauna ma tauhi terei hita au au ana [feet] tauna yawahanihi hita

31.english: so that the multitude wondered when they saw the mute speaking, the injured healed, the lame walking, and the blind seeing—and they glorified the God of Israel.
31.wedau: yamna raketana  [multitude] [wondered] maranaina tauhi inana  [mute] pa  [injured] yawahanihi  [lame] bababara ma  [blind] [seeing—and] tauhi [glorified]  God ana [israel]
31.translation_notes: Primary dimension: Wisdom (0.70); Strong secondary: Love

32.english: Jesus summoned his disciples and said, “I have compassion on the multitude, because they continue with me now three days and have nothing to eat. I don’t want to send them away fasting, or they might faint on the way.”
32.wedau: Yesu [summoned] ana tauvotaghotagho ma riwa [“i] ana [compassion] au  [multitude] yamna tauhi [continue] maitehi tau ina marana [three] maratom ma ana [nothing] da [eat] tau [don’t] [want] da vivohi hita [away] [fasting] bo tauhi ita [faint] au  [way”]
32.translation_notes: Primary dimension: Wisdom (0.81); Strong secondary: Love

33.english: The disciples said to him, “Where should we get so many loaves in a deserted place as to satisfy so great a multitude?”
33.wedau: tauvotaghotagho riwa da tauna [“where] ina ita varahai yamna anatapuhi [loaves] au  [deserted] gabu  da [satisfy] yamna ghe vavahagha  [multitude?”]

34.english: Jesus said to them, “How many loaves do you have?” They said, “Seven, and a few small fish.”
34.wedau: Yesu riwa da hita [“how] anatapuhi [loaves] rura omi [have?”] tauhi riwa [“seven] ma  ghehauhi [small] [fish”]
34.translation_notes: Primary dimension: Wisdom (0.64); Strong secondary: Love

35.english: He commanded the multitude to sit down on the ground;

36.english: and he took the seven loaves and the fish. He gave thanks and broke them, and gave to the disciples, and the disciples to the multitudes.
36.wedau: ma tauna varahai  [seven] [loaves] ma  [fish] tauna verei [thanks] ma [broke] hita ma verei da  tauvotaghotagho ma  tauvotaghotagho da  [multitudes]

37.english: They all ate, and were filled. They took up seven baskets full of the broken pieces that were left over.
37.wedau: tauhi anatapuhi [ate] ma  yawahana tauhi varahai au [seven] [baskets] [full] ana  [broken] [pieces] raketana  voterei au

38.english: Those who ate were four thousand men, in addition to women and children.
38.wedau: raketana aiyai [ate]  [four] [thousand] rava au [addition] da vaivinehi ma natunatuna

39.english: Then he sent away the multitudes, got into the boat, and came into the borders of Magdala.
39.wedau: maratagogi tauna vivohi [away]  [multitudes] varahai au  auwaga ma neꞌi au  [borders] ana [magdala]
